node.text:
I just want to say thank you to all of my followers.  I love this community here and on Facebook.

I love that you’re so willing to help each other with questions.

I love that you’re wanting to get on a health journey and better your health.

I love that you are willing to learn and research from a variety of sources.

I love that you want to make better choices for your children and family.

I love that you understand  that everyone is on a different spot in their health journey and are so willing to help others.

And I love your kindness and support towards me and others.

Happy Thanksgiving!
#givethanks

PS - lots of these pics are before mask days earlier in the year or in 2019!

node.text:
We talked about this a little this weekend on stories…

Gmos are bad, gmos are great.

Organic means nothing.  Organic means so much.

Gluten is fine.  Gluten is harmful.

Dairy is inflammatory, dairy is a great fat.

All of our food has changed since the 90s, none of our food has changed.

Gmo labels are pointless, gmo labels are informative.

Who’s tired of all the extremes?  I am!

Living in extremes is not good for society, your mental health, or your physical health. 

The truth usually lies somewhere in the middle.

For instance:  There are gmos that I’m fine with.  Like changing an apple or potato to not bruise as easily.

Gmos I’m not fine with are the crops that can possibly bring glyphosate into our food supply (corn, soy, canola, cotton (cottonseed oil).

So above is how some of our processed foods have changed over the years.  I post these purely to educate.

In the year 2000, people were so confused as to what was actually being added into our food, so the government created the word organic for processed foods.  This word means:
No artificial dyes 
No artificial sweeteners (sucralose, aspartame, ace-k,etc)
No artificial preservatives 
No artificial flavorings 
No high fructose corn syrup
No hydrogenated oil
No BHT/BHA
No gmos
No glyphosate sprayed on the crops
No added hormones 
No antibiotics 
Animal feed 100% organic and not with glyphosate by-products 
No ionizing radiation

*As none of these requirements above would apply to produce, organic means something completely different for produce.
.

Dr Jess @dr.jess.md is a board certified internal medicine hospitalist. 

She has since left to chase root cause answers for her patients. Dr. Jess teaches that the root cause of disease is usually not just one thing, but a combination of environmental toxicities and pathogens. 

While her teachings and programs have been successful even with the most difficult of patients, she believes health is ultimately in your hands. Her goal is to make you confident, vibrant, and healthier in mind, body, and spirit through education.

In this podcast episode, we look at the problems of mold and parasites and how these can affect your health. 

For mold, we talk about the signs and symptoms of mold toxicity and how it typically occurs. 

It is incredible how mold can contribute to illnesses such as:

👉🏻Depression: a groundbreaking 2007 study showed that major depressive disorder was linked to mold in the home. 

👉🏻Infertility: there are a couple mold species (mycotoxins) that are known endocrine disruptors that bind to estrogen receptors which can lead to estrogen dominance. Women with estrogen dominance or who have hormones that are out of balance can have difficulty getting pregnant or carrying a baby to term.

👉🏻Autoimmune disease: Those with Graves' disease, for example, have the same genotype that those who are sensitive to mold have. Mold has also been linked to sarcoidosis, rheumatoid arthritis, lupus, and Lyme disease. The body can even make gluten antibodies due to mold exposure.

👉🏻Asthma: If your child has asthma symptoms that appear out of the blue or started wetting the bed, mold could be a culprit.

👉🏻Alzheimers: A recent study linked mold exposure to Alzheimers. Breathing mold into the sinus cavity can create neurodegenerative conditions.

The good news is that the body can heal from mold exposure.

Organic cereal? 
Organic chips?
Organic tortillas?

Is it all really necessary?

(Just FYI… top row of pictures contain possible glyphosate, the pics below did not have their crops sprayed with glyphosate).

The food most of us grew up on (depending on your age 😉) was NOT genetically modified to withstand glyphosate! So what changed?

First, GMO stands for genetically modified organism. This means the DNA structure of the plant, like soy for example, has been altered to withstand pesticides being sprayed on it instead of withering or shriveling. Companies sell Roundup Ready crops which are designed to survive applications of Roundup (main ingredient is glyphosate).  Then, the pesticide laden crop is harvested and enters the food supply.  This became common in the 2000s.

Some of the most common GMO foods are corn, soy, canola, and sugar beets. If your food contains one of these crop ingredients, it likely contains GMOs and glyphosate. 

Is glyphosate only a concern for GMO foods?

No, unfortunately. There is a whole list of foods that are sprayed with glyphosate that aren’t GMOs. Wheat, oats and almonds aren’t genetically modified crops but they’re common ones when it comes to being sprayed with glyphosate. 

What is the concern with glyphosate?

-In 2015, the International Agency for Research on Cancer, part of the World Health Organization, reviewed extensive U.S., Canadian and Swedish studies on glyphosate’s human health effects, as well as research on laboratory animals. The IARC classified the chemical as “probably carcinogenic” to humans.

-In 2017, California listed glyphosate in its Proposition 65 registry of chemicals known to cause cancer.

-A 2019 meta-analysis study showed glyphosate increases the risk of cancer by 41%

-In 2021, Bayer (who owns Round Up) announced it would end the sale of glyphosate based herbicides (including Round Up) from the public marketplace. While this is a small victory, it can still be used commercially by farmers so glyphosate will still be in our food supply.

🍼Baby week - 

Just FYI… this is not a comprehensive list.  There is no way to evaluate every brand.  Please take the info from this post (slide 1 and 3) to determine if the prenatal you are taking is a good one!

A woman’s body goes through immense physiological changes during pregnancy, both to nurture the developing baby and to prepare the mother for labor and delivery. 

Like a multivitamin, a prenatal vitamin is there to fill in any nutritional gaps that might not be included in moms diet. 

Some nutrients that are needed more of during pregnancy are folate, iron and omega 3 fatty acids .

👍🏻Folate helps prevent neural tubal defects which are abnormalities of the fetal brain and spinal cord. It is recommended to start taking folate 3 months before becoming pregnant.

👍🏻Iron helps support the development of the placenta and baby. Total blood volume in the pregnant mother typically increases by nearly 50%!

👍🏻Omega 3 fatty acids are a natural fat found in wild caught salmon, walnuts and avocado. This helps promote baby’s healthy brain development.

Also like multivitamins, there are added ingredients that don’t need to be included:

👉🏻synthetic vitamins-vitamins can be sourced from whole food ingredients which are most bioavailable 
👉🏻folic acid-folate is the natural source and much more bioavailable, especially important for those with the MTHFR gene
👉🏻ascorbic acid-this is only part of vitamin c. When it is sourced from a food such as acerola or the amla berry, it encompasses the whole vitamin
👉🏻added sugar-unnecessary and often from a GMO source
👉🏻artificial dyes-unnecessary and can be absorbed into the blood stream

In this podcast Dr.Beck, a pediatric neuropsychologist @drorganicmommy and I talk about several potential toxins that kids face these days. 

First, though, we want to be sure to emphasize that this is not to scare parents or cause undue stress. Taking baby steps at changing out products, especially when it comes to kids, is key. Being informed gives you power. Take this information but don't let it turn into a stressor.

1️⃣Sugar:
Previously, there were two types of sugar used: sugar from sugar cane and from sugar beets. Now there are hundreds of types of sugar. Everything from high fructose corn syrup to fruit concentrates. These are especially found in foods targeted towards kids. 

Too much added sugar affects kids:
-physically with their brain and body; this looks like their ability to focus, process and concentrate.
-relationships with teachers and parents through behavior like hyperactivity
-obesity, heart issues and alzheimers due to lifetime exposure

What can parents do to help?
Be mindful of how you're projecting your thoughts on sugar.
Educate your kids and teach them to recognize how they feel when they eat too much sugar. 
Start with changing one meal to contain less sugar. Breakfast is a great one to work on.

2️⃣Artificial dyes
These are chemical substances that are synthesized from petroleum. They make food more attractive, especially kids food. Study after study have shown that when you remove artificial dyes and preservatives from food it lowers the amount of ADHD symptoms and difficulty concentrating in kids. Artificial dyes can also contribute to tantrums and bad sleep. Luckily, companies are starting to use things like beets and spirulina to color foods. 

3️⃣PFAS
This is a human made substance known for being durable and heat resistant and is also known as a "forever chemical" meaning it doesn't break down. There are thousands of different PFAS. This chemical is found in lots of everyday items; from pots and pans, in water to dental floss and even clothing. The problem is that it impacts our hormones, our immune systems, liver and kidneys, the thyroid, and more. Avoid things that state:
-nonstick
-water resistant
-stain resistant

👶Baby week🍼

The time after a baby is born is one of the most emotion filled times of life! The postpartum time period is often called the "fourth trimester" and for good reason because the body goes through so many changes. 

Along with that there are the demands of a new baby; feeding the baby, the lack of sleep and new motherhood in general. Every birth experience and every baby is different for all of us moms and it can even be different for each pregnancy and birth you experience.

Progesterone and estrogen rise during pregnancy and abruptly drop after the baby arrives. Then oxytocin and prolactin start to rise....the roller coaster of hormones and emotions can really take a toll on new moms. 

This is why it's so important to use products that don't have endocrine disruptors. Endocrine disruptors are "chemicals that may mimic or interfere with the body's hormones, known as the endocrine system." 1 2

What can you do to help those postpartum hormone fluctuations❓

1️⃣Dioxins:
Switch out femine hygiene products for ones with less harmful ingredients. Look for organic pads because those won't have GMO cotton or contain dioxins (due to chlorine bleaching.) Dioxins are linked to hormone disruption and according to the EPA there is "no safe level of exposure to dioxin." 3

2️⃣Phthalates:
Reduce the use of products that may contain phthalates; phthalates can be found in things like scar balms, nipple balms and perennial care items. Even low doses of endocrine disruptors like phthalates can alter the body's sensitive systems. 1

3️⃣BPA:
Look for breast pads, water bottles and other plastic products that are BPA free. BPA has been shown to interact with estrogen receptors and has a tendency to bio-accumulate. 4

✨👉🏻For bottle feeding, my favorite bottles and formulas were just posted on my free baby guide.  Link in bio for it!

👶Baby week🍼- fire retardant chemicals

This post was made, for you to SAVE…and later use when making a baby registry or buying a baby gift.

This post isn’t to shame, hurt feelings or in any way make you feel less adequate as a parent. It is to educate and not to cause fear. All 6 of my children used car seats, strollers and mattresses with flame retardants because that is what was available at the time. (And who knows if I could afford these if I was a new mom today).

The great thing is that we live in a time when people and companies are taking more consideration into what products are made of👏🏼 

There are more and more better options coming out all the time, especially for babies! In 2017 there was just 1 model of car seats available without flame retardants, now so many more! And they still meet federal flammability standards👍🏼

Why look for big ticket items on a baby registry that are free from flame retardants?

“Car seats with added flame retardants put babies and young children in close contact with chemical additives, some of which are known to be carcinogens, hormone disrupters, and developmental toxicants. Babies are especially vulnerable to chemical-laden dust from products like car seats since their systems are still developing.” 1

What materials are companies using that still pass government fire safety testing?

Wool
Polyester
Natural latex
Inherent rayon

Even if you don’t have a better option car seat, safety is the first concern and having your child properly buckled in a safe seat is most important!

@drjoshaxe is a certified doctor of natural medicine (DNM) and clinical nutritionist (CNS) who has helped thousands of people with their health journey. 

It started with his own mother as she battled cancer two times. As she fought cancer, he was able to help her support her body through juicing vegetables, drinking bone broth, eating wild caught salmon, taking turmeric and working on her mindset through positive affirmations. His mom now lives a wonderful, vibrant life. 

In this episode, we talk about:
1️⃣Hormones
Premenopausal women often deal with hypothyroidism. This looks like cold extremities, holding on to body weight and fatigue. Taking time to unplug and rest are crucial. You aren't meant to be "on" and going all the time! 

How can you support your hormone systems? 

Eat things like wild caught fish, berries, seaweeds, green leafy vegetables, avocado, coconut and adaptogens like ashwagandha.

2️⃣Low testosterone and adrenal fatigue in men:

Many men from age 30 on up suffer from this! How can they support their hormone systems?

Lots of healthy fat from coconut and avocado, olive oil, tahini, brazil nuts, pumpkin seeds and healthy fat from grass fed beef as well as plant based protein. 

3️⃣Sleep
Every hormone in the body affects another hormone. Cortisol and melatonin are two hormones that need to be in balance for good sleep. If you get less than 7 hours of sleep per night, you double your risk of cancer, triple your risk of heart disease and triple your risk of coming down with a cold or virus. 

4️⃣Colds and 🦠
If you do come down with an illness, what is the best way to support your immune system?

Chicken bone broth is great. It is full of collagen and glucosamine. Chicken broth both directly and indirectly strengthens your immune system. Since 70% of your immune system is in your gut, having a healthy gut is key to overall immune health.

🍼Baby week🍼

One of the most common questions I get is about baby products. 

Sometimes parents aren’t quite ready to switch out their own products but want to know what the best baby lotion or baby shampoo is. They want what is best for their babies!

If I was creating my own baby registry today, here are some of the ingredients I would avoid:
Parabens 
Phthalates
Talc
Due to consumer demand, these three ingredients have been taken out of many baby products👏🏼 Voting with your dollars makes an impact!!

Other ingredients I would avoid:
Fragrance 
BHA
formaldehyde 
dyes
BPA
and sulfates

1️⃣Why sulfates? 
Sulfates are a surfactant used to create lather but they can also remove the lipid layer from the skin and that can exacerbate atopic dermatitis (eczema). So many babies struggle with eczema! Avoiding sulfates is something you can easily do to help with it.

2️⃣Why BPA?
BPA has been shown to interact with estrogen receptors and acts as an antagonist to signaling pathways. It has been shown to play a role in endocrine disorders like infertility, precocious puberty and hormone related tumors. 

✨These are not the only good items/brands out there.  These are just brands I really like and have used.

✏️Back to school 📕- COLLEGE AGE

While everyone is headed back to school we can’t forget about our college students! 

Not surprisingly, their immu*e systems can take a hit, due to some college kids lifestyles. So here are some tips to help keep college age kids healthy this year!

1️⃣Sleep-
It’s often not a priority-those late nights and early classes can take a toll!

During sleep, the brain not only consolidates learning and memory but also strengthens immune memory. Sleep “reinforces the immune systems ability to remember how to recognize and react to dangerous antigens. Getting enough high quality sleep facilitates the delicate balance of immune function.”1

2️⃣Nutrition-
Nourishing food often takes a back seat and Top Ramen and soda are considered a meal😬

Meals that consist primarily of processed foods and little to no nutrition can negatively affect a healthy immune system. This kind of diet can “promote disturbances in healthy intestinal microorganisms, resulting in suppressed immunity.” 2

👉🏻College students are often on a budget and may think that some of the better options aren’t possible.  Walmart has a great affordable organic line, as seen above. 

And there are some easy changes they can make that are little to no cost:

🍎add a fruit or vegetable to each meal
🥦buy frozen vegetables. These are a great choice because they’re picked at peak ripeness and are generally less expensive
🥚have an egg for a quick, protein filled snack
🌾have organic oats on hand for a quick meal

⛅️open the windows for fresh air
💦drink plenty of filtered water
☀️get some vitamin D through sunshine
🏃‍♀️move your body regularly 
😴get 7-8 hours of sleep
🌱use adaptogens like ashwagandha if stressed
